For a particular backup <name>, the configuration files are read from directories:
 1. /etc/restic/<name>
 2. $HOME/.config/restic/<name>

Where each <name> should have the following

<name>/   Configured name, called as an argument to the backup/restore scripts
  exclude   Files/paths to exclude from backup (optional)
  backup    Files/paths to backup
  repo      The Restic backup path
  passwd    The Restic repository password
  hook      Pre-backup hook (optional)
  retention Retention policy

Onwership rules
- All files must be chmod go-wx.
- The passwd file must be chmod go-rwx.
- The owner of the passwd file uid and $UID must agree.
- All files in the directory must have the same owner.
- Files in the configuration can be links, in which case the ownership applies
  to the linked file.

Best Practice
- The classic 3-2-1 rule keeps three copies on two media with one off-site, yet
  it now needs to be upgraded for modern threats.
- Check that backups (a) contain the right content, and (b) are still valid. A
  write-only backup isn't worth anyone's time.
- Data backup to the cloud *must* be encrypted at source. Even then, don't put
  anything in those backups that you don't want your grandma to see.

Play book
1. Hourly local backups of configuration and work/home data.
2. Daily backup of more static data.
3. Cloud backup of the subset of critical, irreplaceable data.

For cron jobs, create a link to the backup binary with an extended name matching <name>
$ ln -s /usr/bin/backup /etc/cron.daily/backup-data
$ ln -s /usr/bin/backup /etc/cron.hourly/backup-home
$ ln -s /usr/bin/backup /etc/cron.daily/backup-hdd    (external harddrive, to be swapped monthly regularly)
$ ln -s /usr/bin/backup /etc/cron.weekly/backup-cloud

Retention Policy (<name>/retention)
- 24h of hourly local backups
- 7 daily backups
- 4 weekly backups
- 12 monthly backups
- 75 yearly backups

Retention file format is
```
hourly: 24h
daily: 7d
weekly: 1m
monthly: 1y
yearly: 75y
```

Recipes

resticw all backup         # backup and rotate all repositories
resticw all check          # check all respositories
resticw data ncdu          # look for through the files in the latest snapshot
resticw data redu          # look for the largest files ever and add to the exclude list (mark files and manual update)
resticw data rewrite --exclude-file=list.txt --forget   # to remove files from the repo
resticw data mount /mnt/repo  # mount the repo
